<seg id=1> China Plans to Fill Up 1 Million Hectares of Seabed and Settle Down 20 to 30 Million People in the Next Century </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (AFP, Beijing) China Daily, an English newspaper, yesterday reported that China planned to fill up in the next century seabed along coastal areas and settle down 20 to 30 million people. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Experts in the Earth Filling-up Conference held in Xiaoshan of Zhejiang province revealed that the government hopes to fill up 1 million hectares of seabed along the 18,000-kilometer-long seaside areas in the following 4o to 50 years. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> China Daily said that 20 to 30 million people would live in these areas in the next century. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> The paper quoted words from Professor YU Zhiyin that "technologically, it is no problem for China to achieve the goal concerning the earth filling-up, the problem is insufficient funds." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> The news said that even if the plan might cause very big environmental problems, "it is still a magic weapon to ease up the insufficiency of land resource in the next century, especially in view of the vast population in China." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> The plans concerned may also accelerate new trades and increase job opportunities. </seg>
<seg id=8> China plans to invest on the infrastructures in order to get rid of the influence of Asian Economic Crisis. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Zuo zhongmo, deputy secretary general of the conference, said, "this is not only an agricultural problem, the land can be used in comprehensive developing use in several fields, in which forestation, industry and tourism are included." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> Although China is carrying out the "one-child policy", the population in China is expected to increase continually, and will amount to the peak of 1.6 billion in the middle of next century. </seg>
<seg id=11> There are 1.23 billion people in China at present. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> Over 90% of the population congregates on 1/3 of the land. </seg>
</p>
